<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>get into someone’s skin • get under someone’s skin </xh5><p> <i>get into someone’s skin</i>—(coll.) come to a complete understanding of smb.’s inner nature (impersonating a character, etc.): In the church scene, Miss Rehan won her audience ...</p><p> but she never really “<u>got into the skin</u>” of Beatrice.</p><p> <i>get under someone’s skin</i>—(coll.) 1. bother or irritate a person: John is so annoying at times. He really <u>gets under my skin</u>. 2. affect a person so that he becomes very interested in smth.: After a slow start, the play <u>gets under your skin</u> because of its sympathy with the frustrations of small town life. 3. <i>= get into someone’s skin:</i> I think you are interested in—character, shall we say? To <u>get under the skin</u>, as it were, of your criminal.</p> </entry>
